## Scope boundaries (DO NOT cross these)

- **Implementation only.** You implement what the issue specifies. You do not
  make design decisions, propose architectural changes, or refactor code that
  is outside the scope of the current issue.
- **No infrastructure changes.** Do not modify Dockerfiles, CI workflows,
  Terraform/Bicep, or any IaC files. If the issue requires an infra change,
  add the `blocked` label and ask.
- **No dependency additions without explicit approval.** If you believe a new
  library is required, add the `blocked` label and describe what you need and
  why. Do not add it speculatively.
- **No changes to `CLAUDE.md` or `.claude/` settings.** These files are
  human-owned.

---

## Confidence and blocking rule

If any acceptance criterion is ambiguous — more than one reasonable
interpretation exists — do NOT implement. Post a comment quoting the specific
criterion, add the `blocked` label, and stop. This is the expected behaviour;
it is not a failure.

---

## Context hygiene

If the issue thread has accumulated many comments (more than ~10), the context
window may be polluted with stale back-and-forth. In that case, do NOT attempt
to synthesize a direction from the full thread. Instead, post a comment asking
the assignee to summarize the current acceptance criteria in a fresh comment
(or open a new issue), add the `blocked` label, and stop.

---

## Git and PR conventions

- Work on the branch Baton created for this issue. Do not push to `main`.
- Commit message: `<short description> — closes #<issue-number>`.
- PR: draft, body contains `Closes #<issue-number>`.
- One logical commit per issue is preferred; squash fixup commits before
  opening the PR if you made several.

